{{Infobox venue | name = Berlin Wintergarten theatre | nickname = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | fullname = | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1988-035-15, Berlin, Wintergarten.jpg | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = July 1940 | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | address = | location = [[Berlin, Germany]] | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | type = [[Theatre]] | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1887<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = June 1944 | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | production = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = | embedded = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | publictransit = }} [[File:Berlin Wintergarten Potsdamer Straße 2010.jpg|right|thumb|Wintergarten, Potsdamer Strasse, 2010]] The '''Berlin Wintergarten theatre''' was a large [[Music hall|variety theatre]] in [[Mitte (locality)|Berlin-Mitte]].<ref>[https://www.berlin.de/tickets/theater/tipps/buehnen/2225303-2903274-wintergarten-variete.html Berlin.de]</ref>
It opened in 1887 and was destroyed by bombs in June 1944.<ref>[http://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/the-wintergarten-theatre-in-berlin-germany-circa-1926-it-news-photo/152448311 Getty Images]</ref>
The name was taken on by a theatre in Potsdamer Strasse in 1992.
The [[Max Skladanowsky|Skladanowsky brothers]] showcased the first short movie presentation ever at the theatre in 1895, making it the first [[movie theater]] in history. But it was a multi-use variety theatre, not a true kino. As Erwin Panofsky recalls, in about 1905 "there was only one obscure and faintly disreputable ''kino'' in the whole city of Berlin, bearing, for some unfathomable reason, the English name of 'The Meeting Room'".<ref>Panofsky,E, "Style and Medium in the Motion Pictures", <u>Transition</u>, 26, (1937)</ref>
